Shell

  • Computer interaction requires mechanisms to display information and perform operations.
  • Two main approaches:
    • Graphical user interface (GUI) (desktop):
    • Command-line interface (shell):
  • Shell is a program that reads commands and interprets them.

  • Unix shells falls into two basic camps: sh (ksh, bash) and csh (tcsh), each with slightly
    different syntax and semantics.

  • Command comment begins with hash (#) and continues to end of line.

  • Multiple commands on command line separated by semi-colon.
    • $ date ; whoami ; echo Hi There!
  • Tab key auto-completes partial command/file names.
  • Most commands have options, specified with a minus followed by one or more characters, which affect how the command operates.
    • Options are normally processed left to right; one option may cancel another.

File System

  • Directory named / is the root of the file system
  • ~ expands to user’s home directory.
  • . points to the current directories
  • ..points to parent directory above the current directory
  • Absolute pathname is a list of all the directory names from the root to the file name separated by the forward slash character /
  • Relative pathname is file name/path prefixed with working directory.

Quoting

  • Quoting controls how shell interprets strings of characters.
  • Backslash \ : escape any character, including special characters.
$ echo .[!.]*    #globbing pattern

.bashrc .emacs .login .vimrc

$ echo \.\[\!\.\]\* # print globbing pattern

.[!.]*
  • Backquote or $() : execute text as a command, and substitute with command output
$ echo `whoami8` # $ whoami => jfdoe

jfdoe

$ echo $(date)

Tue Dec 15 22:44:23 EST 2015
  • Single quote ' : protect everything (even newline) except single quote.
  • A single quote cannot appear inside a single quoted string.
$ echo Book Report #2

Book Report

$ echo 'Book Report #2'   # no commenting

Book Report #2

$ echo '.[!.]*'          # no globbing

.[!.]*

$ echo '\.\[\!\.\]\*'    # no escaping

\.\[\!\.\]\*

$ echo 

'`whoami`'                # no backquote

`whoami`

$ echo 'abc              # yes newlineEnter

> cdf'                    # prompt “>” means current line is incomplete

abc                       # yes  newline

cdf

$ echo '\''              # no escape single quote

>
  • Double quote " : protect everything except double quote, backquote, and dollar sign
    (variables), which can be escaped.
$ echo ".[!.]*"        # protect special characters

.[!.]*

$ echo "\.\[\!\.\]\*"   # no escaping

\.\[\!\.\]\*

$ echo "`whoami`"      # yes backquote

cs246

$ echo "abc            # yes newlineEnter

> cdf"

abc                     # yes newline

cdf

$ echo "\""            # yes escape double quote

"
  • To stop prompting or output from any shell command, press + c key, causing shell to interrupt current command.

Shell Commands

  • pwd
    • gives the absolute path from the root.
  • cd
    • changes the working directory
    • cd .. changes to directory’s parent directory
    • cd ~ changes to the home directory
    • cd - move to previous working directory (toggle between directories)
  • alias
    • substitutes string for command name
    • alias d=date: no space before/after =. Always use quotes to prevent problems.
    • alias Without argument, print all currently defined alias names and strings.
    • echo
    • write arguments, separated by spaces and terminated with newline.

System Commands

  • sh / bash / csh / tcsh :
    • start subshell to switch among shells</li>
      <li>      echo ${0}` #What shell am I using

  • ls

    • gives a list of all files in current directory (first level)
    • ls -a gives all files including hidden files
    • ls -l generates a long listing (details) for each file
    • ls -R will show the subdirectories recursively, which means it will show all the directories and files within the specified directory.
    • ls -s will also show the size of the files (in blocks, not bytes)
    • ls -h will show the size in “human readable format” (ie: 4K, 16M, 1G etc).
    • ls -d */ will display ONLY the directories from within your current working directory.

  • cp

    • copy files; with the -roption, copy directories.
    • cp -i prompt for verification if a target file is being replaced.
    • cp -r recursively copy contents of a source directory to a target director.

  • mv

    • move files and/or directories to another location in the file hierarchy
    • OR rename source-file if target-file does not exist; otherwise replace target-file.
    • -i prompt for verification if a target file is being replaced.

  • mkdir,rmdir

    • mkdirmakes a new direction
    • rmkdirremoves a directory only if it’s empty
    • rmdir -r dirname removes the directory even if it’s not empty
    • rm filename deletes a file

  • echo

    • write arguments, separated by spaces and terminated with newline

cat and redirection

  • cat f1.txt prints out the file
  • cat -n f2.txt prints out the file with lines numbered
  • cat requires a file name, if no file exits, an error occur. Both error and output display on the screen.
  • a process is attached to 3 streams
    • stdin, the default is the keyboard. can be redirected by <
    • stdout, the default is the screen. Can be redirected by >
    • stderr, the default is also the screen. Can be redirected by 2>
  • ex: cat < f1.txt: shell opens the file, and pass the input into cat. Previously when command is cat f1.txt, cat opens the file.
  • ex: cat f1.txt 2>err.txt puts nothing, as there is no error cat blah.txt 2>err.txt prints nothing to the screen, but stores an error message into the file err.txt
  • recall cat f*.txt, cat will open the files and display.
  • but shell cannot open and redirect more than one files. i.e. cat < f*.txt will fail
  • results can only be present once
  • we can also do cat -n f2.txt >out.txt 2>err.txt we redirect the output to the file out.txt, and the error message to err.txt. Both of out.txt and err.txt are overwrote.

More commands

  • sort f1.txt sorts the file line by line
  • uniq f1.txtremoves all adjacent duplicates in the file
  • sort f1.txt | uniq removes all duplicates, order doesn’t matter
  • cat words*.txt | sort | uniq sorts the files words*.txt
  • date gives the exact date for this time
  • echo "Today is $(date)" Date is processed first. Here the output of a command can also be a parameter of another command
  • \is the escape character that prints the special characters.
  • head, tailand wc
    • head -4 f1.txt presents the first 4 lines of the file f1.txt
    • tail -3 f1.txt presents the last 3 lines
    • wc f2.txt prints out the # of lines, words, characters, newline char count
    • wc -c filename gives only the char count. Same as -l and -w
    • We don’t have to save the intermediate result into a file. We can use pipe |
  • Piping
    • head -5 f1.txt | wc -c moves the output of the first process to be the input of the second process.
    • head -5 f1.txt > c2.txt| wc -c Now the output is written into c2.txt, so there is no output. 0 is printed as nothing is passed to the second process wc

Wildcard Matching and Globbing Pattern

  • If globbing pattern does not match any files, the pattern becomes the argument (including wildcards)
$ echo q*.ww q[a-z].cc       # files do not exist so no expansion

q*.ww q[a-z].cc              # no match
  • *
    • Matches any sequence of characters (0 or more characters)
    • echo *.txt lists all filenames that end with .txt
    • echo f*txt lists all filenames that begin with f and end with .txt
  • ?
  • Matches only 1 character
    • echo re?.txt lists all file names that begin with re, end with .txt and have one character in between.
  • {...,...}
    • Matches any alternative in the set (at least one comma)
    • echo CS{246,1} lists only CS246 and CS1 if they exists, if not, print the pattern.
  • [. . .]
    • Matches one character in the set.
  • [! . . .]
    • Matches one character not in the set
    • CS[!12]* Matches files begin with CS following by a character that is neither 1 nor 2, then any pattern
  • More
    • *does not match all file names in a directory.
    • .* matches all hidden files:
    • ∗ match “.” ,then zero or more characters, e.g., .bashrc, .login, etc., and ., and ..
    • However, matching.and..can be dangerous. $ rm -r .* removes hidden files, and current/parent directory!!!
    • .[!.]*matches all single “.” hidden files but not “ .” and “ . .” directories.
  • find search for names in the file hierarchy.
    • find [ file/directory-list ] [ expr ]
    • -name pattern restrict file names to globbing pattern
    • -type f | dselect files of type file or directory
    • -maxdepth N recursively descend at most N directory levels (0 ⇒ working directory)
    • -not,-a,o logical not, and and or (precedence order).

egrep

  • egrep stands for Extended Global Regular Expression Print
  • egrep pattern fname displays all lines in fname that satisfied the pattern.
  • When working with egrep the pattern is regular expression, not the globbing pattern.
  • -i ignore case in both pattern and input files
  • -n prefix each matching line with line number
  • -v select non-matching lines (invert matching)

regular expressions

  • egrep cs246 index.html prints all the lines from index.html that contain “cs246”
  • egrep "cs246|CS246" index.html and egrep "(cs|CS)246 index.html print all the lines from index.html that contain “cs246” or “CS246”
  • remark (cs|CS)(246|247)is looking for 4 different patterns.
  • "[cC][sS]246" is any combinations
  • [^ ...]matches any one character that is not the set
  • ? indicates 0 or 1 occurrence of the preceding expression
    • ex: [cC][sS] ?246 we are looking for all lines that contains “cs246” with or without the space in between.
  • * indicates 0 or more occurrences of the preceding expression
    • ex (cs)*246we are looking for “246” “cs246” “cscs246” ……
  • + indicates 1 or more occurrences of the preceding expression
    • ex (cs)+246we are looking for “cs246” “cscs246” ……
  • . matches any single character
    • .* matches any string (including empty lines)
    • .+ matches any non-empty string
  • ^ indicates the beginning of the line, and $ indicates the end of the line
    • ^cs246 matches only the line that starts with “cs246”
    • cs246$ matches only the line that ends with “cs246”
    • ^cs246$ matches only the line that only contains with “cs246”

File Permission

  • UNIX supports security for each file or directory based on 3 kinds of users: user,group and other
  • Use ls -l command to print file-permission information
$ ls -l

drwxr-x--- 2 jfdoe jfdoe 4096 Oct 19 18:19 cs246

drwxr-x--- 2 jfdoe jfdoe 4096 Oct 21 08:51 cs245

-rw------- 1 jfdoe jfdoe 22714 Oct 21 08:50 test.cc

-rw------- 1 jfdoe jfdoe 63332 Oct 21 08:50 notes.tex
  • Columns are: permissions, #-of-directories (including “.” and “ . .”), owner, group, file size,
    change date, file name.

  • Default permissions (usually) on:

    • file: rw- r– —, owner read/write, group only read, other none.
    • directory: rwx — —, owner read/write/execute, group/other none.

  • chmod add or remove from any of the 3 security levels.

    • -R recursively modify the security of a directory.
    • Security levels are u for user, g for group, o for other, a for all (ugo)
    • Operator + adds, - removes, = sets specific permission.

I/O Redirection

  • Every command has three standard files: input (0), output (1) and error (2)
  • By default, these are connected to the keyboard (input) and screen (output/error)

  • Redirection allows:
    • input from a file (faster than typing at keyboard),
    • saving output to a file for subsequent examination or processing.
  • Redirection performed using operators < for input and > / >> for output to/from other sources.
    • example: $ sort -n < input 1> output 2> errors
      • < means read input from file rather than keyboard.
      • > , 1>, 2> means (create if needed) file and write output/errors to file rather
        than screen (destructive).
      • >> , 1>>, 2>> means (create if needed) file and append output/errors to
        file rather than screen.

Script

  • A shell program or script is a file (scriptfile) containing shell commands to be executed.
  • First line begins with magic comment: #! (sha-bang) with shell pathname for executing
    the script. Usually #! /bin/bash

  • To create a script, it has no extension vi script3
  • We run the script by calling its name by specify the path.
    • To call the script in the current directory, just add ./script3
    • otherwise, when command script: bash will look for the command in the default directories.

  • BUT, when you create a file, by default, the script will not have the permission to execute.

    • So, we have to change the permission using chmod u+x script3 to give the user permission to run

  • Special parameter variables

    • ${#} number of arguments, excluding script name
    • ${0} always name of shell script
    • ${1}, ${2}, ${3}, … refers to arguments by position (not name), i.e., 1st, 2nd, 3rd, …
    • ${*} and ${@} list all arguments, e.g., ${1} ${2} …, excluding script name.
      • Difference occurs inside double quotes:
        • ${*} arguments as a single string string, e.g., "${1} ${2} . . ."
        • ${@} arguments as separate strings, e.g., ${1}" "${2}" . . .
        • ${?} exit status of the last command executed; 0 often ⇒ exited normally.
  • Arithmetic
    • Arithmetic requires integers, not strings
$ i=3+1       # now i is the string "3+1"

$ j=${i}+2    # now j is the string "3+1+2"


- bash performs these arithmetics with shell-command operator $((expression))

  • Basic integer operations, +, -, *,/, %, with usual precedence, and ( ).

While Loop: printNumber

#!/bin/bash 

x=1

while [  $x -le $1  ]; do

   echo $x

   x=$((x + 1))  # $((...)) syntax for doing arithmetic 

done

For Loop: renameC

#!/bin/bash

# Renames all .cpp files to .cc



for name in *.cpp; do

  mv ${name} ${name%cpp}cc

done
  • *.c represents all files in the current directory that end with .c

    • mv src dest moves the file and deletes the old one
    • ${name} name of the file
    • ${name%c} the name of the file without the trailing ‘c’

Procedures: payday

#!/bin/bash

# Returns the date of the next payday (last Friday of the month)

# Examples:

# payday (no arguments) -- gives this month's payday

# payday June 2016 -- gives payday in June 2016



report () {

  if [ $2 ]; then

     echo -n ${2}

  else

     echo -n "This month"

  fi

  if [ $1 -eq 31 ]; then

    echo "'s payday is on the 31st."

  else

    echo "'s payday is on the ${1}th."

  fi

}



report $(cal $1 $2 | awk '{print $6}' | grep "[0-9]" | tail -1) $1

Intro to C++

Between C and C++

//hello.c

#include <stdio.h>



int main(){

    printf("Hello World\n");

    return 0;   

}

//hello.cc

#include <iostream>// access to output

using namespace std; // direct naming



int main () { // program starts here

  cout << "Hello world" << endl;

  return 0;

}
  • There are a lot of similar syntax between C and C++
  • Most of the C syntax works with C++, we will be highlighting the features of C++
  • C program-files use suffix .c; C++ program-files use suffixes .C / .cpp / .cc
  • main must return integer.
  • In C programming, we include stdio.h, but in C++ we use iostream
  • Using namespace std lets you say cout instead of std::cout
  • By default, main returns 0
  • Note that echo $? returns the returned value of the last executed command/program/etc.

Compilation

g++ -std=c++14 hello.cc -o hello

  • g++ is the compiler
  • std=c++14 c++14 is the standard we are using
    • we have done aliasing in A0 g++14="g++ -std=c++14" Thus we can just type g++14 hello.c
  • -o name generates the executable version as name instead of the default name.
    • the default name is a.out
    • note that there can be only one a.out in a directory, then a.out is the last program we ran.
  • Flag -W generate warning message for different kinds of situations:
    • -Wall prints all warning messages
    • -Werror makes warnings into error so program does not compile

I/O streams

  • Three I/O streams

    • cout for printing to stdout
    • cin for reading from stdin
    • cerr for printing to stderr
    • << endl prints a newline character

  • I/O operations

    • << “puts to”, and it returns cout back
    • cout << "emm" means put the string into output stream
    • >> “get from”, and it returns cin back
//add.cc

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;



int main() {

  int x, y;

  cin >> x >> y;

  cout << x + y << endl;

}
  • cin >> x is simplified to be cin again after execution, so we assign another input to y.
  • This works fine only if the input is two integers.
  • cin is also an object:
    • if the read fails: cin.fail() will be true
    • if EOF: cin.eof() will be true

Examples

readints.cc

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;



int main() {

  int i;

  while (true) {

    cin >> i;

    if (cin.fail()) break;

    cout << i << endl;

  }

}
  • if read fails, break terminates the loop
  • There is an implicit conversion from cin to bool.
    • cin is regarded as true unless it fails
    • Thus we can use cin as a condition!

reatints2.cc

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;



int main() {

  int i;

  while (true) {

    cin >> i;

    if (!cin) break;

    cout << i << endl;

  }

}
  • This program is equivalent to the previous readints.cc example.
  • Note that cin >> i returns the cin stream back.

readInts5.cc

#include <iostream>



// reads all integers and echo to stdout until EOF

// skip non-integer inputs.



using namespace std;

int main () {

  int i;

  while (true) {

    if (!(cin >> i)) {

      if (cin.eof()) break;

      else {

        cin.clear();

        cin.ignore(); 

      }

    }

    else {

      cout << i << endl;

    }

  }

}
  • cin.clear() cin.ignore() every time the reading is not success, we make the cin clear again.

I/O Manipulators

in the library

  • Manipulators are not variables for input/output, but control I/O formatting for all literals/variables after it, continuing to the next I/O expression for a specific stream file
  • Except manipulator setw, which only applies to the next value in the I/O expression.

setw(n)

  • it specifies the minimum number of spaces for the next value to print
  • extra spaces will be printed as leading spaces
int x = 5;

int y = 192;

cout << x << y << endl;

cout << x << " " << y << endl;

cout << setw(4) << x << setw(6) << y << endl;
  • cout << x << y << endl; prints 5192
  • cout << x << " " << y << endl; prints 5_192
  • cout << setw(4) << x << setw(6) << y << endl; prints _ _ _ 5 _ _ _192

hex, dec, oct

  • Each one of them causes all the subsequent integer to be printed in the specific system
  • cout << hex << 95 gives 5f
  • cout << dec << 95 gives 95 back
  • remember that once manipulated, the printed value is set to the system by default. Thus, if you want to print back to decimal system dec
  • make sure to explore, especially about the float numbers

C++ Strings

  • They grow as needed!
  • It’s safer to manipulate strings: string s = "Hello";
  • To define a string, again, using namespace std;
  • To use other method of strings, we have to include other libraries.

String operations

  • * , ==, !=
  • < , <=, >, >=
    • Compares the contents of the string
    • Unlike C, a string is not a pointer
  • s.length() fetch the length of s
  • s[n] to access the n’th character
  • concatenation s3 = s1 + s2: take a copy of s1, and take a copy of s2, concatenate them and assign to s3

  • Once you define a string, if you try to read from cin will be considered as a string.
  • cin >> s;
    • Read a string
    • Skip all leading whitespaces
    • Stop reading at the next whitespace
    • Which means it real one word
  • cout << s
  • If we want to read a complete line including any whitespace. We use getline(cin, s). This means we read a complete line from the standard input.
  • We have may other sources to input, eg. from a file.

Reading from a file

include <fstream> library

  • std::ifstream to read from a file “Input File Stream”
  • std::ofstream to write a file “Output File Stream”

io/fileinput.cc

#include <iostream>

#include <fstream>

using namespace std;



int main () {

  ifstream file{"suite.txt"};

  string s;

  while (file >> s) {

    cout << s << endl;

  }

} //file is closed when it goes out of scope
  • We define a new variable of Input File Stream by: ifstream file{"suite.txt"};
  • Every time you read, it goes to the next input. The file is read word by word.
  • All the tricks we learnt form standard input is valid for reading a file
  • when we encounter the end of the file, file >> s will produce false
  • We DO NOT have to close the file.

Output String Stream

ostringstream to write strings to it.

  • use the library <sstream>
#include <sstream>

int hi = ...;

int lo = ...;

ostringstream ss;

ss << "Enter a value between" << hi << "and" << lo << endl;



cout < ss.str();
  • We push whatever you want to print into the string stream, but nothing is printed to the screen.
  • ss.str(); converts the value in the string stream ss into valid string.

Extra Hints

  • ss >> n When you are trying to read from ss: if the item is string, value is true, else false.

Overloading

  • Allows me to define two function with the same name, but they have to be different in terms of parameter number or parameter type
  • It’s NOT VALID to have the same condition but different return type
int neg(int a){

    return -a;

}



bool neg(bool b){

    return !b;

}
  • if you pass in a boolean value, the second function is executed
  • if you pass in a integer value, the first function is executed


EXAMLE of NOT VALID PROGRAM:

int f(int a, int b=1){

    ...

}



int f(int a){

    ...

}

struct reallyBig{...}



int f(reallyBig rb){...}

int g(reallyBig &rb){...}

int h(const reallyBig &rb){...}//this is always preffered

int f(int &n){...} //INVALID

int g(const int &n){...} // VALID

Dynamic Memory

  • in C, we used mallloc and free, we still have them in C++. But we’ll use other syntax.
  • new and new
struct Node{

    int data;

    Node *next

}

// "new" allocates new memory for the node in the heap;

Node *np = new Node; 

//free the memory

delete np;



//We can also define an array of objects:

Node *myNodes = new Node[10];

//array delete

delete [] myNodes;

Returning by Value/Ptr/Ref

// Version1

Node getMeANode(){

    Node n;

    return n;

}

// Version2: BAD STRATEGY

Node *getMeANode(){

    Node n;

    return &n;

}

// Version3: preferable 

Node *getMeANode(){

    Node *np = new Node;

    return np;

}
  • For version 1, the bigger the data is, the more expensive the precess will be
  • For version 2, when we called the function, new memory is only allocated in the stack. Once we return, all the memory is not suppose to be accessible at all. The new function may . use the same memory.
  • For version 3, we did solve the problem. The Node is allocated on the heap. BUT, make sure to free the memory once done.

Overloading <<, >>

c++/opeartprs/grades.cc

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;



struct Grade {

  int theGrade;

};



// First, we want to overload "<<", we want to fetch the grade and print the grade with the percent sign. The operator should return the reference to the ostream:

ostream &operator<<(ostream &out, Grade &g){

    out << g.theGreade << "%";

    return out; // we are returning a reference

}



// The read operator

istream &operator>>(istream &in, Grade &g) {

  in >> g.theGrade;

  if (g.theGrade < 0) g.theGrade = 0;

  if (g.theGrade > 100) g.theGrade = 100;

  return in;

}



int main () {

  Grade g;

  while (cin >> g) cout << g << endl;

}
  • recall that cout << a returns the cout stream back

Terminologies

  • Error: incorrect program state (“symptom” of the fault)
  • Failure: observable incorrect behaviors
  • Testing is about finding failures
  • Debugging is about fixing faults

Separate Compilation

  • Split your program into modules:
  • Each module includes
    • interface : type definition and the prototype for functions , headers
    • implementation: full details/definitions for every function.
  • Recall that the purpose of declaration is to assert existence. While definition itself present full details and allocate spaces.

Example

c++/separate/example1

//vector.h



struct Vec{

    int x ;

    int y;

};

Vec operator+(const Vec &v1, const Vec &v2);

// vector.cc



#include "vector.h"



Vec operator+(const Vec &v1, const Vec &v2) {

  Vec v;

  v.x = v1.x + v2.x;

  v.y = v1.y + v2.y;

  return v;

}

// main.cc



#include <iostream>

#include "vector.h"



using namespace std;



int main () {

  Vec v = {1,2};

  v = v + v;

  cout << v.x << " " << v.y << endl;

}
  • We compile separately:
    • g++14 -c vector.cc
    • g++14 -c main.cc
    • These lines means : compile only, DONNOT link; DONNOT build executable; produce only object files
    • g++14 vector.o main.o -o main adds the executable file into the file. We link the object files into executable.
  • When decide to make changes to one of the files. We need to recompile only the specific file, and link again.

Rules:

  • Never put using namespace std in any interface file
    • leave the client to choose whether use the notation
  • Never ever compile .h file
  • Never ever include .cc file
  • For example, if we define a variable in vector.h by int globleNum, it’s not working because contends are copied into files that includes vector.h, which may lead to repeat definition. To solve this issue, we can use an extern keyword to indicate the variable in the interface file is just a declaration.
  • i.e. doextern int globleNum orextern const int globleNum

Example Continued

//linearAlg.h

//linearAlg.cc

//main.cc

#include "linearAlg.h"

#include "vector.h"

  • This wont work because the structure definition is defined multiple times every time vector.his included.
  • To prevent files from being included more than one, use include guard, then only one include will be processed.

for vector.h, we do:

#ifndef _VEC_H_

#define _VEC_H_

struct Vec {

  int x;

  int y;

};



Vec operator+(const Vec &v1, const Vec &v2);

#endif
  • The first time to compile this file, the variable _VEC_H is not defined. Then _VEC_H, and the interface is added to the file that includes it. After that, the guard _VEC_H is already defined, so everything is commend out, and is not executed.
  • YOU HAVE TO INCLUDE GUIDE TO EVERY INTERFACE FILE

#include <iostream>

struct Student {

  int assigns, mt, final;

  return assigns * 0.4 + mt * 0.2 + final * 0.4;

  }

};

  Student s {60, 70, 80};

  Student s2 {50, 0, 20};

  cout << s.grade() << endl;

}
  • in the function inside the structure, it is fetching the value we passed into the structure although the values are not defined.
  • All the functions that defined inside the structure definition is called METHOD or MEMBER FUNCTION
  • Methods take a hidden extra parameter called this, which is a pointer to the object which the method is invoked.
    • We don’t usually need to write this unless this is a confusion
    • Eventually, wen we call s.grade()the actual function call is (student2.cc):
float grade(){

    return this->assigns * 0.4 +

           this->mt * 0.2 +

           this->final * 0.4;

}

initializing objects:

  • Student billy{60,70,80} is limited. For example, we may want partial initialization or default initialization.
    • When we do this, a default contractor will grab all the information in the braces and put it into the definition fields accordingly.
    • But this behavior is not enough. So we can overload by writing our own constructor 
struct Student {

  int assigns, mt, final;

  float grade() {

  return assigns * 0.4 + mt * 0.2 + final * 0.4;

  }

  //overwrite the constructor 

  Student(int assigns, int mt, int final){

    this->assigns = assigns;

    this->mt = mt;

    this->final = final;

    }

};
  • Now we can write Student billy{60,70,80} as Student billy = Student{60,70,80}
  • Once we define the constructor, the default one is not valid, which we have to pass three fields to the structure. Student s3; is INVALID.

Initializing in C++

  • int x = 5; is the same as int x(5), int x{5}
  • string s = "hello!" is the same as string s("hello!"), string s{"hello!"}
  • In modern C++, we prefer the curly braces
  • Student *p Jane = new Student{70,80,90} is also VALID

now consider

int z;

  • const variables and references have to be initialized.
  • now, in many cases, the constant are always initialized to be the same, i.e. 5
struct MyStruct{

    const int myConst;

    int &myRef;

}
  • Now we consider the version that we didn’t initialized them
  • Where do we initialized them?
    • constructor body? TOO LATE, because files must be fully constructed by the time the constructor body runs.
    • We need to understand how things work. The key question is what happens when an object is created?
      1. space is allocated
      2. fields are constructed // we have to initialize the constants and references at this stage
      3. the constructor body runs
    • The solution is using MIL, (Member Initialization List), MIL is run before the constructor runs.

MIL

  • Before the constructor body runs, we can initialized using a list with MIL
  • MIL is part of the step when we construct the fields

studentCtorInit.cc

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;



struct Student {

  int assigns, mt, final;

  const int id;  

  Student(int id, int assigns, int mt, int final): 

      id{id},assigns{assigns}, mt{mt}, final{final} //inside braces -> parameter

      { }

    };

}

Important Notes:

  1. You should initialize all fields using MIL.
  2. Fields in MIL are initialized in the order in which they are declared in the class;
  3. MIL can be more efficient than initializing in the body of the constructor , because every object that is not listed in the MIL will be constructed first (default initialization), then initialized.
  4. MIL can initialized any field
  • MIL takes precedence over in-class initialization.
struct Vec{

    int x =0, y = 0;

    Vec(int x): x{x}

        {}

};

  • what is passed to the copy constructor is a constant reference to another structure
  • a complete example: studentCopyCtor.cc
 #include <iostream>

using namespace std;



struct Student {

  int assigns, mt, final;

  float grade() {

    return assigns * 0.4 + mt * 0.2 + final * 0.4;

  }

  Student(int assigns, int mt, int final): assigns{assigns}, mt{mt}, final{final} {

     cout << "Default ctor is being called." << endl;

  }



  Student(const Student &other): assigns{other.assigns},

                                 mt{other.mt},

                                 final{other.final} {

     cout << "Copy ctor is being called." << endl;

  }

};



int main () {

  Student s {60, 70, 80};

  Student s2 = s;

  cout << s.grade() << endl;

  cout << s2.grade() << endl;

}

Note

Every class comes with (default)

  • a constructor,
  • a copy constructor,
  • a copy assignment operator,
  • a destructor
  • a move constructor
  • a move assignment operator
// linkedList.cc

struct Node {

  int data;

  Node *next;

  Node(int data, Node *next): data {data}, next {next} {}

  Node(const Node &n): data {n.data}, next {n.next} {}

  //we want to define a cop ctor here

};



Node *n = new Node{1, new Node{2, new Node{3, nullptr}}};

Node m = *n; 

Node *p = new Node{*n};
  • while initializing n, we are using the constructor
  • while Node m = *n, we are using the copy constructor
  • while p = new Node{*n}, we are using the copy constructor

  • the default copy constructor simply copies the fields
  • we can solve this problem by defining a copy constructor 
*Node (const Node &other): 

    data{other.data}, next{other.next? new Node{*other.next} : nullptr}//deep copy

the copy constructor is invoked:

  • when an object is initialized by another object
  • when an object is passed by value
  • when an object is return by a function
  • more later

Be careful with ctors that can take one parameter 

struct Node{

    ...

    Node(int data): data{data}, next{nullptr}

    {}
  • Overloading, when only one parameter is passed, it construct a linked list with nullptr
  • Now
    • Node n(4); is OK
    • Node n = 4; is OK as well, but we may not want this happen
    • int f(Node 4){...} f(4); runs with no error!
struct Node{

    ...

    explicit Node(int data): data{data}, next{nullptr}

    {}
  • the keyword explicit prevent unwanted behavior
    • Node n(4); is OK
    • Node n = 4; is NOT OK
    • int f(Node 4){...} f(4); is NOT OK
